vide its proof.\n\n```tactics\ndef deriv_interpolated2 {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) :\n    deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) = interpolated_deriv2 x y f := by\n```\n\nTo prove this, we need to show that the derivative of `interpolated_deriv x y f` is `interpolated_deriv2 x y f`.\n\nFirst, let's expand the definitions:\n`interpolated_deriv x y f t = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * (∂/∂t) [f((1-t)x + ty)]`\nWe need to compute the derivative of this expression with respect to `t`.\n\nLet's compute the derivative of the sum:\n`d/dt [∑ i, (y i - x i) * (∂/∂t) [f((1-t)x + ty)] ] = ∑ i, deriv/dt [ (y i - x i) * (∂/∂t) [f((1-t)x + ty)] ]`\n\nSince `(y i - x i)` is constant with respect to `t`, we can pull it out:\n`∑ i, (y i - x i) * deriv/dt [ (∂/∂t) [f((1-t)x + ty)] ]`\n\nThe term `deriv/dt [ (∂/∂t) [f((1-t)x + ty)] ]` is the second derivative of `f` with respect to `t`, which is `∑ j, (∂^2 f / ∂x_j ∂t) ((1-t)x + ty) * deriv/dt [ (1-t)x + ty ]_j`.\nBut `deriv/dt [ (1-t)x + ty ]_j = -x_j + y_j`.\n\nSo, `deriv/dt [ (∂/∂t) [f((1-t)x + ty)] ] = ∑ j, (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty) * (-x_j + y_j)`.\n\nTherefore, the derivative of `interpolated_deriv x y f` is:\n`∑ i, (y i - x i) * (∑ j, (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty) * (-x_j + y_j))`\n`= ∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (-x_j + y_j) * (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty)`\nThis is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty)`.\n\nThis is precisely `interpolated_deriv2 x y f`.\n\nIn Lean, we can prove this using differentiation rules for sums and compositions.\n\n```tactics\nhave h1 : deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) = fun t => ∑ i : Fin n, deriv (fun t => (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)) t := by\n  funext t\n  simp [deriv_sum]\n```\n\nNow, we need to compute the derivative of each term in the sum.\n\n```tactics\nrw [h1]\nfunext t\n```\n\nFor each term `i`, we need to compute `deriv/dt [ (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ]`.\n\nSince `(y i - x i)` is constant with respect to `t`, we can pull it out:\n`(y i - x i) * deriv/dt [ nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ]`\n\nThe derivative of `nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)` with respect to `t` is `∑ j : Fin n, (∂/∂x_j (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) * deriv/dt [ (1 - t) • x + t • y ]_j`.\n`deriv/dt [ (1 - t) • x + t • y ]_j = -x j + y j`.\n\nSo, `deriv/dt [ nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ] = ∑ j : Fin n, (∂/∂x_j (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) * (-x j + y j)`.\nNote that `∂/∂x_j (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))` is `if j = i then (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) else 0`.\nSo, this simplifies to `(∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) * (-x i + y i)`.\n\nTherefore, `deriv/dt [ (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ] = (y i - x i) * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) * (-x i + y i)`.\nThis is `(y i - x i) * (y i - x i) * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) = (y i - x i)^2 * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`.\n\nWait, that's not right. Let's think again.\n\nThe derivative of `A * B(t)` is `A * B'(t)`.\nHere, `A = (y i - x i)`, `B(t) = nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`.\n`B'(t) = deriv/dt [ nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ]`.\nAs calculated before, `B'(t) = ∑ j, (∂/∂x_j (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) * (-x j + y j)`.\nSince `∂/∂x_j (nth_partial i f (z))` is `if j = i then (∂f/∂x_i) (z) else 0`, we have:\n`B'(t) = (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) * (-x i + y i)`.\n\nTherefore, `deriv/dt [ (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ] = (y i - x i) * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) * (-x i + y i)`.\nThis is `(y i - x i) * (y i - x i) * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) = (y i - x i)^2 * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`.\n\nBut `interpolated_deriv2 x y f t` is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`.\nThis is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (∂^2 f / ∂x_i ∂x_j) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`.\n\nThere's a mismatch. The expression we derived involves `(y i - x i)^2 * (∂f/∂x_i) ...`, while the target has `(y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (∂^2 f / ∂x_i ∂x_j) ...`.\n\nLet's recompute the derivative more carefully.\n\nThe function is `F(t) = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`.\nThe derivative is `F'(t) = ∑ i, deriv/dt [ (y i - x i) * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ]`.\nSince `(y i - x i)` is constant with respect to `t`, we have:\n`F'(t) = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * deriv/dt [ (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ]`.\nLet `g(t) = (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`.\n`g'(t) = deriv/dt [ (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ]`.\nUsing the chain rule, `g'(t) = (∂/∂z_j (f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)) ) * deriv/dt [ (1 - t) • x + t • y ]_j` evaluated at `z = (1-t)x + ty`, where `z_j = x_j`.\nBut `f` is `E n → ℝ`, so `f(z)` is a scalar. The partial derivatives are `∂f/∂z_j`.\n`∂f/∂z_j` evaluated at `z = (1-t)x + ty` is `(∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty)`.\n`deriv/dt [ (1 - t) • x + t • y ]_j = -x_j + y_j`.\nSo, `g'(t) = ∑ j, (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty) * (-x_j + y_j)`.\n\nTherefore, `F'(t) = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * (∑ j, (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty) * (-x_j + y_j))`.\nThis is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (-x_j + y_j) * (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty)`.\nThis is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty)`.\nThis is the same as `interpolated_deriv2 x y f t`.\n\nSo, the expression we derived is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty)`.\nBut `interpolated_deriv2` involves `nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f`.\n`nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f` is `∂/∂x_i (∂f/∂x_j) = ∂^2 f / ∂x_i ∂x_j`.\n\nSo, our computed derivative is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (∂f/∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty)`.\nThis is not the same as `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (∂^2 f / ∂x_i ∂x_j) ((1-t)x + ty)`.\n\nThere's a mistake in our calculation. Let's compute `deriv/dt [ (y i - x i) * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ]` again.\nUsing product rule: `d/dt [A * B(t)] = A' * B(t) + A * B'(t)`.\nHere, `A = (y i - x i)` (constant), `B(t) = (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`.\nSo, `d/dt [ (y i - x i) * (∂f/∂x_i) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) ] = 0 *