      "\n  funext t\n  simp [interpolated_deriv, interpolated_deriv2]\n  have h1 : Differentiable ℝ (fun (t : ℝ) => ∑ i : Fin n, (y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) := by\n    apply Differentiable.sum\n    intro i hi\n    apply Differentiable.mul\n    · -- Show differentiable\n      apply differentiable_const\n    · -- Show differentiable\n      apply Differentiable.nth_partial f\n      all_goals\n        apply Differentiable.interpolator x y\n  have h2 : Differentiable ℝ (fun (t : ℝ) => ∑ i : Fin n, ∑ j : Fin n, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) := by\n    apply Differentiable.sum\n    intro i hi\n    apply Differentiable.sum\n    intro j hj\n    apply Differentiable.mul\n    · -- Show differentiable\n      apply differentiable_const\n    · -- Show differentiable\n      apply Differentiable.mul\n      · -- Show differentiable\n        apply differentiable_const\n      · -- Show differentiable\n        apply Differentiable.nth_partial\n        all_goals\n          apply Differentiable.interpolator x y\n  have eq1 : deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => ∑ i : Fin n, (y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t =\n      ∑ i : Fin n, deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => (y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t := by\n    simp [deriv_sum]\n  have eq2 : deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => ∑ i : Fin n, ∑ j : Fin n, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t =\n      ∑ i : Fin n, ∑ j : Fin n, deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t := by\n    simp [deriv_sum]\n  have eq3 : deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => (y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t =\n      (y i - x i) * deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t := by\n    simp [deriv_mul, deriv_id'', mul_comm]\n  have eq4 : deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t =\n      (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t := by\n    simp [deriv_mul, deriv_id'', mul_comm]\n  have eq5 : deriv (fun (t : ℝ) => (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))) t =\n      ∑ j : Fin n, (nth_partial j (fun (z : E n) => (nth_partial i f z)) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)) * (y j - x j) := by\n    simp [deriv.comp, deriv_interpolator, deriv_id'', mul_comm]\n    all_goals\n      try { norm_num }\n      try { tauto }\n  rw [eq1, eq2, eq3, eq4, eq5]\n  all_goals\n    try { ring }\n    try { tauto }",
      "\n```\n\nWe need to compute the derivative of `interpolated_deriv x y f` and show it equals `interpolated_deriv2 x y f`.\n\nThe function `interpolated_deriv x y f` is `t ↦ ∑ i, (y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`.\nLet's denote `g(t) = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`.\nWe need to compute `deriv g`.\n\nUsing the definition of derivative for a sum:\n`deriv g(t) = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * deriv [ (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) ]`\n\nUsing the chain rule:\n`deriv [ (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) ] = (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) * deriv [interpolator x y t]`\n\nThe derivative of `interpolator x y t` is `y - x`.\nSo:\n`deriv [ (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) ] = (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) * (y - x) i`\n\nTherefore:\n`deriv g(t) = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * ( (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) * (y - x) i )`\n`deriv g(t) = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * (y - x) i * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`\n\nThis is precisely `interpolated_deriv2 x y f t`.\n\nIn Lean, we can compute this as follows:\n\n```tactics\n  simp [deriv_sum, deriv_mul, deriv_id'', mul_comm]\n  <;> field_simp [Fin.sum_univ_succ, mul_add, add_mul]\n  <;> ring\n```\n\nWait, actually, we need to think more carefully. The function `interpolated_deriv` is a sum over `i` of terms `(y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`. To take the derivative of this sum with respect to `t`, we need to apply the product rule for each term.\n\nFor each `i`, the term is `(y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`.\nThe derivative of this term with respect to `t` is:\n`(y i - x i) * deriv [ (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) ] + deriv [ (y i - x i) ] * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`\n\nThe derivative of `(y i - x i)` with respect to `t` is `0`.\nThe derivative of `(nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)` with respect to `t` is, by the chain rule:\n`deriv [ (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) ] = (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) * deriv [interpolator x y t]`\n\nThe derivative of `interpolator x y t` with respect to `t` is `y - x`.\nTherefore, the derivative of the term is:\n`(y i - x i) * ( (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t) * (y - x) i ) + 0 * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`\n`= (y i - x i) * (y - x) i * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`\n\nSumming over `i`, we get:\n`∑ i, (y i - x i) * (y - x) i * (nth_partial i f) (interpolator x y t)`\n\nThis is precisely the definition of `interpolated_deriv2 x y f t`.\n\nIn Lean, we need to compute the derivative of the sum and show it equals the sum of the derivatives. This involves applying the product rule for derivatives and the chain rule.\n\nThe Lean proof would look something like this:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.InnerProductSpace.Dual\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Integral.IntervalIntegral.FundThmCalculus\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.InnerProductSpace.Calculus\nimport Noperthedron.Nopert\nimport Noperthedron.PoseInterval\nimport Noperthedron.Global.Basic\n\nopen scoped RealInnerProductSpace\n\nnamespace GlobalTheorem\n\nprivate abbrev E (n : ℕ) := EuclideanSpace ℝ (Fin n)\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef interpolator {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (t : ℝ) : E n :=\n  (1 - t) • x + t • y\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef interpolated {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) : ℝ → ℝ  :=\n  f ∘ interpolator x y\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef Differentiable.interpolator {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) :\n    Differentiable ℝ (interpolator x y)  := by\n  unfold GlobalTheorem.interpolator\n  fun_prop\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef Differentiable.interpolated {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) (fc : ContDiff ℝ 2 f) :\n    Differentiable ℝ (interpolated x y f)  := by\n  have := Differentiable.interpolator x y\n  have := fc.differentiable (by norm_num)\n  unfold GlobalTheorem.interpolated\n  fun_prop\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef interpolated_deriv {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) (t : ℝ) : ℝ :=\n  ∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) 