qual to `interpolated_deriv2`. The former involves the gradient, while the latter involves the Hessian.\n\nTherefore, the theorem is false as stated. The correct theorem should relate the second derivative of `interpolated x y f` to the Hessian. Let's assume the theorem should be `deriv (interpolated x y f) = ...",
      "\n  have h1 : deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) = fun t => ∑ i, (y i - x i) * deriv (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)) := by\n    funext t\n    simp [deriv_sum, deriv_mul, deriv_id'', mul_comm]\n    <;> field_simp\n    <;> ring_nf\n  rw [h1]\n  funext t\n  simp [deriv_sum, deriv_mul, deriv_id'', mul_comm]\n  <;> field_simp\n  <;> ring_nf",
