      "\n  have h1 : deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) = deriv (f ∘ interpolator x y) := by\n    simp [interpolated_deriv]\n  rw [h1]\n```\n\nNow we have `deriv (f ∘ interpolator x y)`. We apply the chain rule.\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : deriv (f ∘ interpolator x y) = deriv f (interpolator x y) • deriv (interpolator x y) := by\n  apply deriv.comp\n  all_goals\n    try { \n      apply Differentiable.interpolated \n      apply differentiableAt_id \n      all_goals \n        try { \n          apply Differentiable.interpolator \n        } \n    }\n    try { \n      apply Differentiable.interpolator \n    }\n```\n\nNow we need to compute `deriv (interpolator x y)`. The function `interpolator x y` is `(1 - t) • x + t • y`. The derivative with respect to `t` is `y - x`.\n\n```tactics\nhave h3 : deriv (interpolator x y) = y - x := by\n  simp [interpolator]\n  <;> fun_prop\n```\n\nNow we can substitute `h2` and `h3` into our expression.\n\n```tactics\nrw [h2, h3]\n```\n\nNow we have `deriv f (interpolator x y) • (y - x)`. We need to expand this using the definitions of derivatives and show it equals `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`. \n\nThe expression `deriv f p • v` is `∑ k, (f_k p) v_k`. So, `deriv f ((1-t)x + ty) • (y - x) = ∑ k, (f_k ((1-t)x + ty)) (y k - x k)`. \n\nTo get the sum expression `∑ i, ∑ j, ...`, we need to expand this further. The term `f_k` can be related to the partial derivatives. The expression `(f_k ((1-t)x + ty))` is the `k`-th partial derivative of `f` at the point `(1-t)x + ty`. \n\nThe target sum is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`. This is a sum over pairs of indices `i, j` of the product of coordinate differences and the `i,j`-th partial derivative of `f`.\n\nTo prove the equality, we need to use the Taylor expansion of `f` around the point `(1-t)x + ty`. The function `f` can be approximated by its Taylor expansion: `f(p) ≈ f(p) + ∑ k, (f_k p) (h_k) + ...`. The derivative `deriv f p` is the linear map `L(h) = ∑ k, (f_k p) h_k`. \n\nThe strategy will be to use Lean's derivative rules for compositions and relate it to the sum expression. This likely involves expanding the derivative using the chain rule and then showing it equals the sum.\n\n```tactics\nhave eq1 : deriv f (interpolator x y) • (y - x) = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * (f i ((1 - t) • x + t • y)) := by\n  simp [deriv, Fin.sum_univ_succ, Fin.sum_univ_zero, differentiableAt_id, differentiableAt_const, differentiableAt_add, differentiableAt_mul, mul_comm]\n  <;> ring\n```\n\nNow we need to show that `∑ i, (y i - x i) * (f i ((1 - t) • x + t • y))` equals `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`. \n\nThis requires expanding the sum `∑ i, (y i - x i) * (f i ((1 - t) • x + t • y))` further. The term `f_i` can be related to the partial derivatives. The expression `(f_i ((1-t)x + ty))` is the `i`-th partial derivative of `f` at the point `(1-t)x + ty`. \n\nThe target sum is `∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`. This is a sum over pairs of indices `i, j` of the product of coordinate differences and the `i,j`-th partial derivative of `f`.\n\nTo prove the equality, we need to use the Taylor expansion of `f` around the point `(1-t)x + ty`. The function `f` can be approximated by its Taylor expansion: `f(p) ≈ f(p) + ∑ k, (f_k p) (h_k) + ...`. The derivative `deriv f p` is the linear map `L(h) = ∑ k, (f_k p) h_k`. \n\nThe strategy will be to use Lean's derivative rules for compositions and relate it to the sum expression. This likely involves expanding the derivative using the chain rule and then showing it equals the sum.\n\n```tactics\nhave eq2 : ∑ i, (y i - x i) * (f i ((1 - t) • x + t • y)) = ∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) := by\n  have h5 : ∀ i, f i ((1 - t)",
      "\n```\n\nNow, we need to prove `deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) = interpolated_deriv2 x y f`.\n\nLet's compute:\n`interpolated_deriv x y f` is `fun t => ∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`\nSo, we need to differentiate `∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)` with respect to `t`.\n\nUsing the differentiation rule for sums:\n`deriv (∑ i, f_i(t)) = ∑ i, deriv (f_i(t))`\n\nFor each term `deriv ((y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))`:\nUsing the product rule:\n`deriv (u * v) = deriv u * v + u * deriv v`\nwhere `u = y i - x i` (constant with respect to t) and `v = nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`\n\nSo:\n`deriv ((y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))`\n= `(y i - x i) * deriv (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))`\n+ `0 * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`\n= `(y i - x i) * deriv (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))`\n\nNow, applying the chain rule to `deriv (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))`:\nLet `g(t) = (1 - t) • x + t • y`\nThen `deriv (nth_partial i f (g(t))) = D(nth_partial i f) (g(t)) • deriv g(t)`\n`deriv g(t) = deriv ((1 - t) • x + t • y) = -x + y`\nSo:\n`deriv (nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))`\n= `D(nth_partial i f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) • (-x + y)`\n= `∑ j, (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f)) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) * (y j - x j)`\n\nPutting it all together:\n`deriv ((y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y))`\n= `(y i - x i) * (∑ j, (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f)) ((1 - t) • x + t • y) * (y j - x j))`\n= `∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f)) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`\n\nSumming over `i`:\n`∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i (nth_partial j f)) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`\nThis is exactly `interpolated_deriv2 x y f`.\n\nSo in Lean 4, we need to use the appropriate differentiation rules.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.InnerProductSpace.Dual\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Integral.IntervalIntegral.FundThmCalculus\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.InnerProductSpace.Calculus\nimport Noperthedron.Nopert\nimport Noperthedron.PoseInterval\nimport Noperthedron.Global.Basic\n\nopen scoped RealInnerProductSpace\n\nnamespace GlobalTheorem\n\nprivate abbrev E (n : ℕ) := EuclideanSpace ℝ (Fin n)\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef interpolator {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (t : ℝ) : E n :=\n  (1 - t) • x + t • y\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef interpolated {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) : ℝ → ℝ  :=\n  f ∘ interpolator x y\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef Differentiable.interpolator {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) :\n    Differentiable ℝ (interpolator x y)  := by\n  unfold GlobalTheorem.interpolator\n  fun_prop\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef Differentiable.interpolated {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) (fc : ContDiff ℝ 2 f) :\n    Differentiable ℝ (interpolated x y f)  := by\n  have := Differentiable.interpolator x y\n  have := fc.differentiable (by norm_num)\n  unfold GlobalTheorem.interpolated\n  fun_prop\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef interpolated_deriv {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) (t : ℝ) : ℝ :=\n  ∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)\n\nprivate noncomputable\ndef interpolated_deriv2 {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) (t : ℝ) : ℝ :=\n  ∑ i, ∑ j, (y i - x i) * (y j - x j) * (nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) ((1 - t) • x + t • y)\n\ndef deriv_interpolated {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) :\n    deriv (interpolated x y f) = interpolated_deriv x y f := by\n  sorry\n\ndef deriv_interpolated2 {n : ℕ} (x y : E n) (f : E n → ℝ) :\n    deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) = interpolated_deriv2 x y f := by\n```\n\nNow, we need to compute the derivative of `interpolated_deriv x y f`.\n`interpolated_deriv x y f` is `fun t => ∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`\nSo, we need to differentiate `∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)` with respect to `t`.\n\nUsing the differentiation rule for sums:\n`deriv (∑ i, f_i(t)) = ∑ i, deriv (f_i(t))`\n\nFor each term `deriv ((y i